        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">CD discussed the development of the moral sense in both animals and humans in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> 1: 70–104.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Johnson refers to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4207.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">D. Johnson 1822</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Mohout: i.e. mahout, keeper and driver of an elephant (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1347.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Chambers</hi></ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">See <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4207.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">D. Johnson 1822</ref>, pp. 65–6.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">For CD’s sources on the origin of language and the application of the theory of natural selection to language, see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> 1: 56 and n. 34. Johnson refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3233.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Friedrich Max Müller</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">The verb stems are as follows: [textgreek[klu’w]]: to hear, attend to, [textgreek[tla’w]]: to endure, submit.</note>
        </div>        
            
